From 01e5a4868e8d39117c22fe13660978723613ba94 Mon Sep 17 00:00:00 2001
From: Dan on Selwyn <dan@awto.au>
Date: Sat, 18 Jul 2026 13:09:15 +1000
Subject: [PATCH] lib: translate strncpy_from_user to Rust (linux-rs TU 35)

do_strncpy_from_user()/strncpy_from_user(): word-at-a-time copy of a
NUL-terminated string from a userspace pointer into a kernel buffer,
with a byte-at-a-time fallback for unaligned src/dst or a mid-word
page fault. Sibling of strnlen_user_rs.rs (TU 34, same file family:
asm/uaccess.h, asm/word-at-a-time.h) but with a genuinely different
control-flow shape: TWO unsafe_get_user() sites with DIFFERENT fault
targets, not one shared efault label.

Reuses every uaccess shim strnlen_user_rs.rs established in
rust/helpers/uaccess.c (rule 0014): rust_helper_strnlen_user_task_size_max,
untagged_addr_ul, access_ok, user_read_access_begin/_end,
unsafe_get_user_ul. Adds exactly one new shim,
rust_helper_unsafe_get_user_u8 -- a byte-sized sibling of
unsafe_get_user_ul needed for the byte_at_a_time fallback loop
(unsafe_get_user(c, src+res, efault) where c is char, not
unsigned long). Same fault contract as its word-sized sibling,
verified the same way: a real page fault traps into the kernel,
consults the EX_TYPE_UACCESS_ERR_ZERO extable entry, resumes at the
compiled-in fixup -- the Rust caller's None is driven by real
hardware fault delivery.

The two unsafe_get_user() sites do NOT share a fault target (rule
0020 shared-label/distinct-value, extended): the word-at-a-time
loop's unsafe_get_user(c, ..., byte_at_a_time) falls back into the
byte-at-a-time loop on a fault -- NOT an immediate -EFAULT, since a
partial word may be unreadable while its trailing bytes are still
reachable one at a time -- while the byte-at-a-time loop's own
unsafe_get_user(c, ..., efault) returns -EFAULT directly. Translated
as a `break` out of the word loop (carrying res/max forward) vs a
direct `return -EFAULT`, never collapsed into one match arm despite
both being the None case of a fault-safe read.

has_zero/create_zero_mask/find_zero/fls64/zero_bytemask reuse the
exact reimplementation already established in lib/string_rs.rs and
lib/strnlen_user_rs.rs (rule 0016, third instance of the same
header-inline family: arch/riscv/include/asm/word-at-a-time.h +
include/asm-generic/bitops/fls64.h). zero_bytemask(mask) is riscv's
literal `(mask)` #define identity (arch/riscv/include/asm/
word-at-a-time.h:48) -- reused verbatim as `let mask = data;`, not
reimplemented as a computation, matching string_rs.rs's own
established pattern.

IS_UNALIGNED(src, dst): CONFIG_HAVE_EFFICIENT_UNALIGNED_ACCESS is
unset in this build's .config (same finding string_rs.rs's module doc
already documents for sized_strscpy), so the live macro arm is the
real alignment test, not the 0 stub -- translated as a genuine check,
exercising the byte-at-a-time fallback for real on unaligned
src/dst, not skipped as dead code.

can_do_masked_user_access() is, as in strnlen_user, a compile-time 0
on this arch (riscv never #defines masked_user_access_begin) -- not
translated, same spirit as rule 0026. Four additional pre-checks
(might_fault, should_fail_usercopy, kasan_check_write,
check_object_size) were individually verified against their real
header definitions to be compile-time no-ops for this exact
.config (CONFIG_PROVE_LOCKING/DEBUG_ATOMIC_SLEEP/
FAULT_INJECTION_USERCOPY/HARDENED_USERCOPY all unset, no KASAN
config enabled) -- genuine no-ops for this build, not a judgement
call generalised across configs, same bar the sibling TU set for
can_do_masked_user_access().

strncpy_from_user is a plain (non-_GPL) EXPORT_SYMBOL in the C
original; #[export] always emits EXPORT_SYMBOL_GPL -- tracked,
license-inert deviation per rule 0001 (CONFIG_MODULES unset).

Verification:

1. Build: `dev.py build` -> BUILD OK; RUSTC compiled
   lib/strncpy_from_user_rs.o fresh (confirmed via .cmd file and
   object timestamp, real clippy/missing_docs-strict rustc
   invocation, zero warnings). nm vmlinux confirms
   strncpy_from_user (T, global text); 5 real undefined-symbol
   callers found across the tree (fs/namei.o, fs/xattr.o,
   kernel/sys.o, kernel/reboot.o, mm/maccess.o) -- genuinely linked
   and called, not dead code.

2. Oracle (tier 2.5, bench/diff_strncpy_from_user.{c,rs}): the real
   unsafe_get_user() fault path can't be exercised from a portable
   host program (no way to trigger a real page fault at a chosen
   address and resume via extable outside the kernel) -- isolates the
   fault-free word-at-a-time scanning/copying arithmetic instead,
   covering: count<=0/negative-count edge cases, alignment (0..7 x
   0..7 src/dst offsets, exercising IS_UNALIGNED's real branch),
   NUL-position sweep, and count-boundary sweep (below/at/above
   strlen+1). Additionally identified and exercised for real (not
   just inspection-verified) a SECOND -EFAULT trigger this function
   has that strnlen_user doesn't: the pure-arithmetic "hit max, but
   max < count" post-loop branch, which needs no real fault at all --
   just max < count, driven by the address-space-limit truncation the
   caller does before calling in. `scripts/diff_oracle.py
   strncpy_from_user` -> ORACLE 2.5 PASS, 2500 cases / 5000 output
   lines byte-identical; re-run manually at 50000 cases with a
   different seed, also byte-identical, with the arithmetic -EFAULT
   path genuinely hit 7272/50000 times and matching on every case.
   The genuine unsafe_get_user() hardware-fault path itself remains
   inspection-verified + boot-verified only, same constraint
   strnlen_user's landing documented.

3. `dev.py check` (build + boot + report): 16/16 KUnit suites,
   ORACLE PASS, INIT REACHED. SPDX provenance check: "PASS
   lib/strncpy_from_user_rs.rs == lib/strncpy_from_user.c
   (GPL-2.0)", 34/34 translated files pass, 0 fail.

